write_utf8(c('# Abstract','',
'Latin America faces a persistent structural transformation challenge: growth episodes have often coexisted with export baskets concentrated in primary and resource-linked activities. This paper studies economic complexity, productive capabilities and diversification opportunities in Latin America, with Bolivia as a focal case. It uses a locally reconstructed Harvard Atlas HS92 four-digit country-product-year panel covering 6,497,429 observations, 242 countries, 1,243 products and 1995-2023, combined with processed country-year macro controls. The analysis computes RCA, diversity, ubiquity, HHI, entropy, annually standardized ECI, projected PCI, Product Space proximity, density and opportunity scores. Bolivia records ECI = -1.236, diversity = 82, HHI = 0.124 and primary export share = 62.7 percent in 2023. A strict absolute opportunity screen finds few close high-complexity candidates; a relative Bolivia-specific screen identifies 11 strategic bets, 239 incremental extensions, 107 transformational long shots, 454 middle-range candidates, 41 low-priority products and 286 excluded products. The contribution is an auditable workflow that translates complexity metrics into a cautious policy-screening framework. The analysis is descriptive and does not claim causal identification.'), p('paper/abstract.md'))
write_utf8(c('# Research Contribution','',
'The contribution is empirical, interpretive and reproducible rather than methodological novelty. The project applies established economic-complexity concepts to a locally reconstructed Latin American panel and documents the full chain from data inventory to validation, figures, dashboard and paper.','',
'Its Bolivia contribution is the dual opportunity classification. The strict absolute typology shows that close high-complexity quick wins are scarce. The relative typology then organizes Bolivia\'s constrained universe into feasible screening categories without changing validated rankings.','',
'The regional contribution is to situate Bolivia among Latin American productive structures rather than treating it as an isolated case. The reproducibility contribution is the separation of raw data, processed caches, public samples, local paths and validation outputs.'), p('paper/research_contribution.md'))
write_utf8(c('# Executive Summary','',
'This repository studies economic complexity and structural transformation in Latin America using a reproducible local-data workflow. It focuses on Bolivia because its export basket illustrates the tension between feasible related diversification and more ambitious transformation.','',
'Validated Bolivia 2023 indicators are ECI = -1.236, diversity = 82 RCA products, HHI = 0.124 and primary export share = 62.7 percent. The Product Space diagnostics distinguish 701,978 analytical edges from the 698-edge visual network. Density and Opportunity Gain use the full analytical matrix.','',
'The opportunity analysis preserves the strict absolute classification and adds a relative Bolivia-specific screen. The eligible universe contains 852 products. Relative categories include 11 strategic bets, 239 incremental extensions, 107 transformational long shots, 454 middle-range candidates, 41 low-priority products and 286 excluded products. These labels are screening categories, not investment prescriptions.','',
'The econometric evidence is observational. Fixed-effects models are reported as associations, not causal estimates. The repository includes public samples, tests, dashboard code, paper outputs, audit reports and file-policy documentation.'), p('paper/executive_summary.md'))
write_utf8(c('# Key Findings','',
'- The processed panel covers 6,497,429 country-product-year observations, 242 countries, 1,243 HS92 four-digit products and 1995-2023.','- Bolivia 2023 has ECI = -1.236, diversity = 82, HHI = 0.124 and primary export share = 62.7 percent.','- Bolivia\'s HHI is slightly above the regional median reported in validation outputs, so concentration is interpreted comparatively rather than in isolation.','- The Product Space contains 701,978 analytical positive edges and a 698-edge visual subset; density calculations use the analytical matrix.','- The relative opportunity screen identifies 11 strategic bets and 239 incremental extensions, but these categories are not automatic policy recommendations.','- Fixed-effects models show descriptive associations between complexity and performance indicators; no causal identification is claimed.'), p('paper/key_findings.md'))
write_utf8(c('---','title: "Bolivia Productive Capabilities And Diversification Screen"','format: html','---','','# Policy Brief','','## Diagnosis','','Bolivia\'s validated 2023 export indicators show ECI = -1.236, 82 HS4 products with RCA >= 1, HHI = 0.124 and primary export share = 62.7 percent. These figures indicate a constrained productive position relative to more complex regional economies, but they do not imply immobility.','','## Evidence','','The Product Space analysis suggests that many high-transformation products are distant from Bolivia\'s current RCA basket. Under conservative absolute thresholds, close high-complexity opportunities are scarce. A relative Bolivia-specific screen identifies 11 strategic bets, 239 incremental extensions, 107 transformational long shots, 454 middle-range candidates, 41 low-priority products and 286 excluded products.','','## Interpretation','','Product-level rankings should be interpreted as analytical screening tools rather than investment prescriptions. They do not incorporate firm capabilities, infrastructure constraints, environmental impacts, political economy, financing needs or detailed demand conditions.','','## Policy Use','','- Use incremental extensions to identify near-term learning and supplier-development opportunities.','- Use strategic bets to select candidates for deeper sector feasibility studies.','- Treat transformational long shots as longer-horizon capability-building questions.','- Prioritize public goods such as standards, logistics, technical training, export information and coordination before sector-specific support.','- Evaluate pilots transparently and avoid treating Product Space rankings as automatic subsidy lists.'), p('paper/policy_brief.qmd'))
write_utf8(c('---','title: "Appendix"','format: html','---','','# Appendix A. Technical Notes','','This appendix summarizes details that support the main paper without overloading the narrative. Full validation evidence is stored in the `docs/` and `outputs/tables/csv/` folders.','','## RCA and MCP','','RCA is computed as the country-product export share divided by the world product export share. MCP equals one when RCA is at least one and zero otherwise.','','## ECI and PCI','','ECI is recomputed by year and standardized within each annual distribution. Longitudinal changes describe relative position. PCI is an internal projection from country ECI to products.','','## Product Space','','The analytical Product Space for 2023 contains 701,978 positive edges. The 698-edge graph is a visual subset. Density and Opportunity Gain are computed from the analytical matrix.','','## Models','','Fixed-effects models include country and year fixed effects with country-clustered standard errors. They are descriptive and not causal.'), p('paper/appendix.qmd'))
write_utf8(c('# Methodology','',
'This document summarizes the validated methodology used in the repository. It does not rerun the full pipeline.','','## RCA and MCP','','Revealed comparative advantage is the product export share in the country divided by the product export share in the world. The binary MCP matrix equals one when RCA >= 1.','','## Country-Year Indicators','','Diversity counts RCA products. HHI is the sum of squared product export shares. Entropy measures dispersion. Primary and manufacturing shares are computed from HS section groupings.','','## ECI and Temporal Comparability','','ECI is computed separately for each year from the binary RCA matrix. The second eigenvector is standardized within year and sign-oriented to correlate positively with diversity. Because the series is annually standardized, ECI supports relative within-year comparison and ranking. Longitudinal changes should be described as changes in relative annual position, not as absolute units of productive capabilities gained or lost.','','## PCI','','PCI is a projected product index created by projecting country ECI through the product side of the RCA matrix and standardizing within year. It is not claimed to be an independent external product-side eigen-decomposition.','','## Product Space and Density','','Product proximity is based on conditional co-export relationships. The analytical 2023 Product Space contains 701,978 positive edges. The 698-edge visual graph is used for legibility only. Density and Opportunity Gain use the full analytical matrix.','','## Opportunity Scores','','The absolute classification preserves conservative global thresholds. The relative classification ranks products within Bolivia\'s eligible universe using percentile-normalized density, projected PCI, Opportunity Gain, market size and demand growth. Scores are screening tools, not investment recommendations.','','## Econometric Models','','The fixed-effects models are observational. They include country and year fixed effects and country-clustered standard errors. They are used to describe associations, not causal effects.'), p('docs/METHODOLOGY.md'))
write_utf8(c('# ECI And PCI Technical Validation','',
'ECI is recomputed year by year from the binary RCA matrix using the country-side normalized reflection matrix `D_c^-1 M D_p^-1 M\'`. The second eigenvector is selected, standardized within year and sign-oriented to correlate positively with diversity.','',
'Because ECI is standardized separately each year, it supports within-year comparison and ranking. Changes over time should be described as changes in relative position within the annual ECI distribution, not as absolute units of productive capability gained or lost.','',
'PCI is a projected product index: product values are obtained by projecting country ECI through the product side of the RCA matrix and standardizing within year. It is not a separate external product-side eigen-decomposition.','',
'Validation summary from Phase 2: annual ECI means are effectively zero after standardization; annual ECI standard deviations equal one; annual PCI standard deviations equal one.','',
'Interpretation rule: use language such as "Bolivia\'s relative position in the annual ECI distribution" rather than "Bolivia gained or lost ECI units of productive capabilities."'), p('docs/ECI_PCI_TECHNICAL_VALIDATION.md'))

esc_html <- function(x){x<-gsub('&','&amp;',x,fixed=TRUE); x<-gsub('<','&lt;',x,fixed=TRUE); gsub('>','&gt;',x,fixed=TRUE)}
q <- readLines(p('paper/main.qmd'), warn=FALSE, encoding='UTF-8')
body <- character(); in_yaml <- FALSE; in_ul <- FALSE
close_ul <- function(){ if(in_ul){ body <<- c(body,'</ul>'); in_ul <<- FALSE } }
for (ln in q) {
  if (ln == '---') { in_yaml <- !in_yaml; next }
  if (in_yaml || grepl('^(title|subtitle|author|date|format|bibliography):', ln)) next
  if (grepl('^# ', ln)) { close_ul(); body <- c(body, paste0('<h1>', esc_html(sub('^# ', '', ln)), '</h1>')) }
  else if (grepl('^## ', ln)) { close_ul(); body <- c(body, paste0('<h2>', esc_html(sub('^## ', '', ln)), '</h2>')) }
  else if (grepl('^!\\[', ln)) { close_ul(); alt <- sub('^!\\[([^]]*)\\].*$', '\\1', ln); src <- sub('^!\\[[^]]*\\]\\(([^)]+)\\).*$', '\\1', ln); body <- c(body, paste0('<figure><img src="', esc_html(src), '" alt="', esc_html(alt), '"><figcaption>', esc_html(alt), '</figcaption></figure>')) }
  else if (grepl('^- ', ln)) { if(!in_ul){body<-c(body,'<ul>'); in_ul<-TRUE}; body <- c(body, paste0('<li>', esc_html(sub('^- ', '', ln)), '</li>')) }
  else if (grepl('^\\|', ln)) { close_ul(); body <- c(body, paste0('<p class="table-line">', esc_html(ln), '</p>')) }
  else if (nzchar(trimws(ln))) { close_ul(); body <- c(body, paste0('<p>', esc_html(ln), '</p>')) }
}
close_ul()
heading_idx <- grep('^<h[12]>', body)
toc <- character()
if (length(heading_idx)) {
  heading_text <- gsub('<[^>]+>', '', body[heading_idx])
  heading_ids <- tolower(gsub('[^a-z0-9]+', '-', iconv(heading_text, from='UTF-8', to='ASCII//TRANSLIT')))
  heading_ids <- gsub('(^-|-$)', '', heading_ids)
  heading_ids <- make.unique(ifelse(nzchar(heading_ids), heading_ids, paste0('section-', seq_along(heading_ids))), sep='-')
  for (j in seq_along(heading_idx)) {
    body[heading_idx[j]] <- sub('^(<h[12])>', paste0('\\1 id="', heading_ids[j], '">'), body[heading_idx[j]], perl=TRUE)
  }
  toc <- c('<nav id="toc" class="toc"><strong>Contents</strong><ol>', paste0('<li><a href="#', heading_ids, '">', heading_text, '</a></li>'), '</ol></nav>')
}
